  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Poor communication at every stage&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;In May my GP, instructed by the Professor of Allergy at Guy's, referred me for Skin Patch testing at Guy's and I was given a General Allergy appointment at Guy's for end of September. It was cancelled and then rearranged at my local hospital QEH Woolwich (which is no closer using public transport) for October and again at General Allergy, where I would not have got an appointment for Patch testing till the following March or later. After hours of phone calls and being given a phone number to leave messages on which had a deactivated voicemail I eventually spoke to the Service Manager at Guys, who agreed my referral to Guys for Patch testing should be honoured. I spoke to and emailed Cutaneous Allergy Service and was given 3 timed appointments. A few days before the appointments I had still not received any paper or text confirmation so rang the department who fortunately were still able to give me those appointments as they were still free. If I had just turned up at the times I'd be given over the phone I would have been turned away and have to start again! 
  Please look also at improving communication at the Dermatology clinic. It is not clear how your name is called out. Do you look at the screens constantly or wait till your name is spoken quietly? If you are told your name will be called in a few minutes and you're still waiting 45 .United later (as I was), what are you meant to do? Also, staff need to make it clear that you may not be able to have a shower for up to 6 days!! I though I'd be able to shower after the 2nd appointment following the hottest recorded temperature in UK!! Only when I asked about showering as I left the clinic was I told I had to wait another 3 days. This is not clear in the literature or from staff. Please improve your communication and try to imagine you are a new patient coming to the Dermatology department.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
